(Prosper EDA)¶

by (Gamal Eldin Samy)¶

Introduction¶

Prosper is a peer-to-peer (P2P) lending platform. Investors on the site can invest as little as $25 in personal loans to other people. All personal loans issued on the site are unsecured personal loans with fixed interest rates. Prosper uses a ranking system on loans to rate loans on a scale of AA to F. AA have the lowest yields, and are the least likely to default. F loans have the highest yield, but are most likely to default. However, peer-to-peer lending is still a relatively unknown investment opportunity.

The Prosper dataset(last updated on 03/11/2014) contains four kinds of variable categories during 2006 to 2014:

  • Loan Status : The status of the loan listed such as Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue.

  • Borrower Data : Basic properties about borrowers such as credit score, occupation, employment status, etc.

  • Loan Data : Basic properties about the loan such as length of the loan(term), Borrower APR, etc.

  • Credit Risk Matrices : Matrices measured the risk of loans, such as Credit grade, Prosper Score, bank card utilization, etc.

  • Prosper Customers with history: How many loans they previously received, if they paid on time or not, etc.

The Questions:¶

  • What was the reason behind the company reconstruction in 2009?
  • What affects the borrowers APR or interest rate?

General Properties of The Dataset¶

In [5]:

The number of variables has been reduced from 81 to 38

Many variables' data types need to be modified, converted and ordered. So I'll make a copy first then proceed.

According to the sheet giving a description of available variables, there are two versions of the company. The thing that made me pay a visit to a reviewing website and I quote:

When investors consider Prosper as an investment they need to remember that there have really been two iterations of the company. Prosper 1.0 was from their beginning in 2006 to 2008 when underwriting standards were very lax (the minimum credit score was 520) and investor returns, on average, were negative. Prosper 2.0 is from 2009 to the present day when underwriting standards improved dramatically (minimum FICO score is now 640) and returns for investors have been much better.

Also to zoom in on the controlling factors of BorrowerAPR, it's worth noting the following:

One unique part of the way Prosper ranks borrowers is that they use more than just a loan grade there is also a Prosper Score ranging from 1-11. This is a score that they have developed internally based on the payment history of actual borrowers on their platform. They use both the Prosper score and the borrowers credit information to determine the interest rate and the estimated loss rate.

Maybe it's a good idea to split data into groups reflecting the iterations of the company, especially that Credit rating columns are filled with NaN values and historical Prosper customer data used for building ProsperScore is not available for listings prior to Q3 2009

  • BorrowerAPR

Stated Monthly Income¶

The distribution is highly skewed to the right. Maybe showing the data on a log scale makes a diffence.

In [22]:
def log_trans(x, inverse=False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10, x)
    
#  transforming the bins to the log scale
log_binsize = 0.025
bins = 10 ** np.arange(log_trans(10), log_trans(prosper_clean['StatedMonthlyIncome'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[10, 5])
plt.hist(data=prosper_clean, 
         x = 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 
         bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')

#  limiting the data to values between 500 and 50K where most of the data fall between
plt.xlim(5e2, 5e4)

#  using proper tick values and their right locations
plt.xticks([1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4, 5e4], 
           ['1k', '2k','5k', '10k', '20k', '50k'])
plt.xlabel('Stated Monthly Income ($)')
plt.title('Stated Monthly Income Distribution in Log-scale')
plt.show();

The distribution follows a normal distribution on the log scale and the mean value seems to sit around $ 5K

Credit Risk Metrics¶

Before Q3 2009, Credit Grade was the metric displayed for investors to show how healthy the borrower's credit is. So, I'll start with it and see how it's distributed.

In [33]:
def disp_prctg(df, var, top_padding=500):
    """
    Display percentage of each category annotated to the corresponding bar
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    df: variable name referencing to the dataframe
    var: string value of the column name
    """
    n_points = df.shape[0] - pd.isna(df[str(var)]).sum()
    cat_counts = df[str(var)].value_counts()
        # loop through each pair of locations and labels
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):

        # get the text property for the label to get the correct count
        count = cat_counts[label.get_text()]
        pct_string = '{:0.2f}%'.format(100*count/n_points)

        # print the annotation just below the top of the bar
        plt.text(loc, count-top_padding, pct_string, ha = 'center', color = 'w')
        

plt.figure(figsize=[15, 5])

disp_prctg(prosper_clean, 'ProsperRating', top_padding=600)
  • Before 2009, the distribution was normal with a peak around the C grade, with little variation between different grades in the number of loans in each bucket.
  • However, after 2009 there not only is there a more noticeable peak around the C grade but also, the variance between categories percentages increased. Especially for HR and AA ratings, where percentages got cut in half!
  • The new metric for credit rating lowered the percentage of HR loans and AA's as well. It also prohibited giving loans to borrowers with no credit (NC)

As mentioned previously, Credit Grade is based on buckets,designed by Prosper, to pigeonhole borrower's credit score of an independent credit reporting agency. While Prosper Rating is based on the company's Prosper Score as well as borrower credit information. I'll start the investigation by creating a plot matrix between borrower credit numeric variables and borrower history with Prosper.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Most of the variables are normally distributed. Others were skewed, but showed normal distribution on log-scale such as monthly income, revolving credit, available bank credit, debt-to-income ratio, and prosper outstanding principal

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • Borrowers are mostly low-to-mid class citizens with income ranges from 25k to 75k.
  • Loans are mostly geared toward consolidating other debts.
  • Unlike home ownership, having a verifiable source of income helps borrowers land a loan.
  • loans have a bette chance ending up completed rather than defaulted or charged-off.
  • Bank Card Utilization should be a minimum. And it seems they decided a cut-off value around 1%, above which the listing is subject to other variables deciding whether it would be accepted or not and surely will increase the Borrower Rate.
  • When comparing Credit Grade and Prosper Rating, the new metric for credit rating lowered the percentage of HR loans and AA's as well. It also prohibited giving loans to borrowers with no credit (NC)

Bivariate Analysis¶

Prosper Iterations¶

Company's first iteration showed a moderate weak correlation between Credit Grade and Borrower APR. After applying the new model in the third quarter of 2009, Prosper Rating became a more refined metric for Borrower APR.

Borrower APR Controlling Factor¶

Borrower APR is strongly and negatively correlated with Prosper Rating. Increasing Prosper Rating, guarantees lower Borrower APR.

Prosper Rating Contributing Elements¶

  • Prosper Rating affected by both Prosper Score and borrower Credit Score. However, it's shown that Prosper Rating is more sensitive to changes in Prosper Score compared to borrower Credit Score. Proving that Prosper values its own data over external sources.
  • Internal data, such as ScorexChangeAtTimeOfListing showed a positive correlation with Prosper Score.
  • External data, such as InquiriesLast6Months, DelinquenciesLast6Months, BankcardUtilization showed negative correlaion with Prosper Score.
  • Borrower debt-to-income ratio showed a negative correltion with Prosper Score.
  • Borrower recommendations don't make any difference when it comes to APR

Effects of 2008 Recession on Borrower APR and following Recovery¶

  • After facetting Borrower APR over the years, the 2008 global recession showed its mark. A high rate of 0.32 became more and more dominant through 2008. It too the company nearly 3 years to recover and lower its rates.
